# Fixing Lint Errors

## Never delete code to silence a linter

Deleting a variable, map, or function purely to fix an `unused` lint error destroys
valuable work (e.g. firmware analysis data, lookup tables, documentation).

**Always fix the root cause instead:**

| Lint error | Wrong fix | Right fix |
|---|---|---|
| `var X is unused` | Delete `X` | Add a function/method that uses `X` |
| `SA9003: empty branch` | Delete the `if` block | Remove the `if` and keep (or inline) any useful logic |
| `errcheck: unchecked error` | Delete the call | Assign and handle the error |

## Example: unused map

```go
// ❌ BAD — deletes firmware-analysis data to silence linter
// var errInfoCodeDesc = map[int64]string{ ... }

// ✅ GOOD — expose the map through a function so it is referenced
func errInfoCodeDescription(code int64) string {
    return errInfoCodeDesc[code]
}
```

## Example: empty branch (SA9003)

```go
// ❌ BAD — empty body, linter complains, logic intent is lost
if err := doThing(); err == nil {
    // nothing
}

// ✅ GOOD — remove the if entirely; keep the actual verification below
doThing() // or drop if the call result is unused
```
